<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="157" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[178,1085,893,973]" pageId="30" pageNumber="157">
D i a g n o s i s: Specimens of this genus resemble superficially those of 
<emphasis box="[970,1085,895,916]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="157">Inconnexus</emphasis>
OPITZ, but 
<emphasis box="[288,426,923,944]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="157">Silvanoclerus</emphasis>
specimens differ by having much smaller eyes (compare 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 44-56" captionStartId="8.[178,218,1441,1463]" captionTargetBox="[186,1064,221,1411]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[177,1084,211,1431]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 44-56: Various organs. 44-52 Pronota. (44) Silvanoclerus beechi. (45) Labasiella bimaculate. (46) L. boyaca. (47) L. Cochabamba. (48) L. mcclarini. (49) L. eugeniae. (50) L. robles. (51) L. solervicensi. (52) L. transversalis. 53-54 Heads. (53) Inconnexus lunarus. (54) Silvanoclerus dilatus. 54A-54B Generalized shape of the last maxillary palpomeres. (54A) Securiform. (54B) subsecuriform. 55-56 Mesodermal reproductive organs of Amphelissus meieri. (55) Female. (56) Male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3762398" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3762398/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="157">Figs 53, 54</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="157" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="30.[178,1085,989,1070]" pageId="30" pageNumber="157">
D e s c r i p t i o n: This genus was adequately described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ" firstAuthor="OPITZ" pageId="30" pageNumber="157" pagination="29 - 117" refId="ref18217" refString="OPITZ W. (2017 a): Classification, Natural History, and Evolution of the Subfamily Peloniinae OPITZ (Coleoptera: Cleroidea: Cleridae). Part VII. The World Genera of Peloniinae (Coleoptera: Cleridae). Linzer biologische Beitrage 49 (1): 29 - 117." type="journal article" year="2017" yearSuffix="a">OPITZ (2017a)</bibRefCitation>
. Additional characteristics are: Pronotal sides reticulated, epipleural angle faintly developed, elytral 2° setae prominent, and elytral posterior slope gradual.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
